          "title": "The purged remnant — humble, truthful, undisturbed (3:11-13)",
          "body": "The eschatological purging produces a community whose character is the precise antithesis of the city described in 3:1-4. Three removals and three retentions define it. Removed: shame for past deeds (3:11a) — because the sin has been purged, not simply excused. Removed: the proud, exulting ones from God's holy mountain (3:11b) — the civic and religious elites whose arrogance made them unteachable. Removed: haughtiness on God's holy mountain (3:11c). Retained: a humble and lowly people (ani and dal — two Hebrew words for lowly/poor/meek) who take refuge in the name of the Lord (3:12). The remnant's ethics in 3:13 are strikingly speech-centered: no wrong, no lies, no deceitful tongue. This mirrors the purified lips of 3:9 — the eschatological community is defined by truthful speech because it has received the gift of purified lips. The final image is pastoral and Davidic: 'they will feed and lie down with no one to make them tremble' (3:13) — the Ezekiel 34:28 / Micah 4:4 / Psalm 23:2 picture of the flock under the true Shepherd. The community produced by judgment is not merely surviving; it is flourishing in undisturbed security. Moo's principle applies here: the prophetic vision of the remnant is never merely ethnic survival but always ethical transformation (Moo, Pillar NTC methodology, applied to prophetic literature)."
